            <div class="qec-step-body">Record supporting facts, data, examples, or quotes that address the question. This is your personal mark scheme — the content a strong answer must include. Use your textbook, e-book, and course materials. <strong>Keep this separate</strong> from the space where you will attempt your answer.</div>
            <ol class="qec-ol">
              <li>Read and research the topic with your question in mind.</li>
              <li>Note down key points, technical terms, and worked examples.</li>
              <li>Include specific details — names, figures, acronyms, stages — not just vague ideas.</li>
            </ol>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="qec-step">
          <div class="qec-letter c">C</div>
          <div>
            <div class="qec-step-title">Conclusion &nbsp;<span style="font-size:13px;color:var(--green);font-weight:600">Synthesise into a final answer</span></div>
            <div class="qec-step-body">Synthesise the evidence into a final summary, claim, or answer — often forming a thesis statement or a full exam-style response. This is where knowledge becomes understanding. Close your notes, attempt the answer from memory, then compare it to your evidence to find the gaps.</div>
            <ol class="qec-ol">
              <li>Close all notes and course materials completely.</li>
              <li>Read the question only and write a full answer from memory — in complete sentences.</li>
              <li>Open your evidence and compare your answer honestly against it.</li>
              <li>Note every gap or error — these become your priorities for the next study session.</li>
            </ol>
          </div>
        </div>
        <hr class="qec-divider">
        <div class="qec-why">
          <div class="qec-why-title">Why active recall works</div>
          <div class="qec-why-body">Retrieval practice — the "testing effect" — consistently outperforms re-reading in research on long-term retention. Every time you struggle to recall something and succeed, the memory trace becomes stronger. Getting an answer wrong is not failure; it is the most useful information your revision session can produce.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="recall-rules">
          <div class="recall-rule"><div class="recall-rule-dot">&#8594;</div><div>Never passively re-read your notes. This creates an illusion of knowing without building actual memory.</div></div>
          <div class="recall-rule"><div class="recall-rule-dot">&#8594;</div><div>Write complete sentences, not bullet points. Mirror real exam conditions in your practice.</div></div>
          <div class="recall-rule"><div class="recall-rule-dot">&#8594;</div><div>Attempt the full question before checking evidence. No partial peeking.</div></div>
          <div class="recall-rule"><div class="recall-rule-dot">&#8594;</div><div>Leave a gap between building your evidence and doing your recall — at least a few hours, ideally a day.</div></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>`,
    leitner:`<div class="sup-body">
      <div class="sup-h">Spaced Repetition — The Leitner System</div>
      <div class="sup-sub">Use the "Sort by Confidence" button in the Question Generator to sort your questions into these three boxes. Study Box 1 most, Box 3 least.</div>
      <div class="leitner-boxes">
        <div class="lbox b1">
          <div class="lbox-num">Box 1</div>
          <div class="lbox-title">Don't Know</div>
          <div class="lbox-freq">Review: Every study session</div>
          <div class="lbox-desc">Your highest priority. These are the questions you cannot yet answer with confidence. Spend the most time here.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="lbox b2">
          <div class="lbox-num">Box 2</div>
          <div class="lbox-title">Unsure</div>
          <div class="lbox-freq">Review: Every other session</div>
          <div class="lbox-desc">Almost there. You have some understanding but need reinforcement before these become reliable.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="lbox b3">
          <div class="lbox-num">Box 3</div>
