      <div class="leitner-rules-list">
        <div class="l-rule"><div class="l-rule-arrow">&#8594;</div><div>Start every study session with <strong>Box 1</strong> questions. Work through Box 2, then Box 3.</div></div>
        <div class="l-rule"><div class="l-rule-arrow">&#8594;</div><div>Answer a Box 1 question correctly &#8594; move it to Box 2. Answer a Box 2 correctly &#8594; move it to Box 3.</div></div>
        <div class="l-rule"><div class="l-rule-arrow">&#8594;</div><div>Get a Box 3 question wrong at any point &#8594; return it <strong>immediately to Box 1</strong>.</div></div>
        <div class="l-rule"><div class="l-rule-arrow">&#8594;</div><div>The goal is to move all questions to Box 3 — but always prove it by attempting, never by assuming.</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>`,
    ideal:`<div class="sup-body">
      <div class="sup-h">PO3: The IDEAL Framework</div>
      <div class="sup-sub">Use this structure for every 6-mark and 9-mark answer. Work through each letter in order — skipping any step is why answers stay at Level 1 or 2.</div>
      <div class="ideal-steps">
        <div class="ideal-step">
          <div class="ideal-letter i">I</div>
          <div>
            <div class="ideal-step-name">Identify — State the concept clearly</div>
            <div class="ideal-step-desc">Define or state what you are being asked about. Keep this to 1–2 sentences. Do not over-explain at this stage — save the depth for the development steps.</div>
            <div class="ideal-step-tip">Example: "[Concept] is [definition]. It is commonly used to [purpose/context]."</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ideal-step">
          <div class="ideal-letter d">D</div>
          <div>
            <div class="ideal-step-name">Develop — Make a point and explain it fully</div>
            <div class="ideal-step-desc">Make a substantive point. Explain a feature, benefit, or characteristic using subject-specific vocabulary. Do not just state the point — explain the effect it has and link it directly to the scenario. 2–3 sentences minimum per development point.</div>
            <div class="ideal-step-tip">6-mark: 2 developed points. 9-mark: 3 developed points. Each D step is worth marks — never write only one.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ideal-step">
          <div class="ideal-letter e">E</div>
          <div>
            <div class="ideal-step-name">Evidence / Example — Apply it to the scenario</div>
            <div class="ideal-step-desc">Support your point with a direct, specific reference to the scenario in the question. Generic answers are capped at Level 1. Using the exact context of the scenario — the business type, their problem, their situation — is what pushes you into Level 2 and 3.</div>
            <div class="ideal-step-tip">Use the specific details: "For a hospital developing a patient appointment system, this would mean..." — not just "for a business".</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ideal-step">
          <div class="ideal-letter a">A</div>
          <div>
            <div class="ideal-step-name">Alternative / Another side — The counterpoint</div>
            <div class="ideal-step-desc">Present the other side of the argument: a limitation, risk, drawback, or opposing view. This must be developed — do not just state it in one word. This step is what separates Level 2 from Level 3 in almost every marking scheme.</div>
            <div class="ideal-step-tip">Analyse: one limitation is enough. Discuss and Justify: both sides are required to reach Level 3 — examiners are instructed to cap one-sided responses.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ideal-step">
          <div class="ideal-letter l">L</div>
          <div>
            <div class="ideal-step-name">Link / Conclude — Make a clear, decisive final judgement</div>
            <div class="ideal-step-desc">Weigh up both sides and reach a conclusion. State which argument wins and explain why — specifically for this scenario. Never sit on the fence. For 9-mark answers this must be 2–3 sentences. A weak or missing conclusion is one of the most common reasons students lose the top 1–2 marks.</div>
            <div class="ideal-step-tip">Do not just repeat your first point. Reference the scenario and acknowledge both sides before giving your verdict.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>`,
    bands:`<div class="sup-body">
      <div class="sup-h">PO3: Structure &amp; Mark Bands</div>
      <div class="sup-sub">Know exactly what the examiner is looking for at each level — and what steps to take to get there.</div>
      <div class="marks-comparison">
        <div class="marks-col m6">
          <div class="marks-col-header">6-Mark Answer — Structure</div>
          <div class="marks-col-body">
            <div class="struct-step"><span class="struct-num">Step 1</span><span><b>Identify</b> — Define the concept. (1–2 sentences)</span></div>
            <div class="struct-step"><span class="struct-num">Step 2</span><span><b>Point 1 + Development</b> — Make a point, explain it, link to scenario. (2–3 sentences)</span></div>
            <div class="struct-step"><span class="struct-num">Step 3</span><span><b>Point 2 + Development</b> — Second point, explain it, link to scenario. (2–3 sentences)</span></div>
            <div class="struct-step"><span class="struct-num">Step 4</span><span><b>Conclude</b> — Final judgement on the scenario. (1–2 sentences)</span></div>
            <div style="font-size:12px;color:var(--text3);margin-top:4px">Target: 120–180 words · ~8–10 minutes</div>
            <div class="band-table">
              <div class="band-row l3"><div class="band-marks">5–6</div><div class="band-desc"><b>Level 3</b> — Two or more developed points with clear scenario links. Balanced judgement with a conclusion.</div></div>
              <div class="band-row l2"><div class="band-marks">3–4</div><div class="band-desc"><b>Level 2</b> — At least one developed point with some scenario link. May lack a clear conclusion.</div></div>
              <div class="band-row l1"><div class="band-marks">1–2</div><div class="band-desc"><b>Level 1</b> — Points stated with little or no development. Mostly knowledge recall only.</div></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="marks-col m9">
          <div class="marks-col-header">9-Mark Answer — Structure</div>
          <div class="marks-col-body">
            <div class="struct-step"><span class="struct-num">Step 1</span><span><b>Identify</b> — Define concept, set the context. (1–2 sentences)</span></div>
            <div class="struct-step"><span class="struct-num">Step 2</span><span><b>Point 1</b> — Main point in favour. Explain and link to scenario. (2–3 sentences)</span></div>
            <div class="struct-step"><span class="struct-num">Step 3</span><span><b>Point 2</b> — Second angle. Explain and link to scenario. (2–3 sentences)</span></div>
            <div class="struct-step"><span class="struct-num">Step 4</span><span><b>Alternative</b> — Counterpoint or limitation. Develop it fully. (2–3 sentences)</span></div>
            <div class="struct-step"><span class="struct-num">Step 5</span><span><b>Extra point</b> (optional) — Third supporting point. Recommended for Level 3.</span></div>
            <div class="struct-step"><span class="struct-num">Step 6</span><span><b>Conclude</b> — Weigh both sides. Clear, reasoned verdict. (2–3 sentences)</span></div>
            <div style="font-size:12px;color:var(--text3);margin-top:4px">Target: 220–320 words · ~12–15 minutes</div>
            <div class="band-table">
              <div class="band-row l3"><div class="band-marks">7–9</div><div class="band-desc"><b>Level 3</b> — Multiple fully developed points, consistent scenario links, balanced view with counterpoints, clear reasoned conclusion.</div></div>
              <div class="band-row l2"><div class="band-marks">4–6</div><div class="band-desc"><b>Level 2</b> — Some development, partially linked to scenario. Some balance shown but conclusion underdeveloped.</div></div>
              <div class="band-row l1"><div class="band-marks">1–3</div><div class="band-desc"><b>Level 1</b> — Minimal development or reasoning. Little scenario reference. No clear conclusion.</div></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>`,
    starters:`<div class="sup-body">
      <div class="sup-h">PO3: Sentence Starter Banks</div>
      <div class="sup-sub">Click any starter to copy it to your clipboard. Use these when you get stuck moving from a point into development, or when you need to connect your answer to the scenario. Replace the [placeholders] with your own content.</div>
